04551nam a22005775i 9781400873425DE-B159720210225050953.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210225t20152015nju    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)984652219  a97814008734257 a10.1515/97814008734252doi  a(DE-B1597)459994  a(OCoLC)919297115  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aHG925b.S24 2015 7aBUS0450002bisacsh04a332.4/942231 aSandbu, Martin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aEurope's Orphan :bThe Future of the Euro and the Politics of Debt /cMartin Sandbu.  aPilot project. eBook available to selected US libraries only 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (336 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tONE. A Giant Historic Mistake? -- tTWO. Before the Fall -- tTHREE. Greece and the Idolatry of Debt -- tFOUR. Ireland: The Private Is Political -- tFIVE. Europe Digs Deeper -- tSIX. Righting the Course: From Bail-Out to Bail-In -- tSEVEN. If Europe Dared to Write Down Debt -- tEIGHT. Europe’s Real Economic Challenges -- tNINE. The Politics That the Euro Needs -- tTEN. Great Britain or Little England? -- tELEVEN. Remembering What the Euro Is For -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOriginally conceived as part of a unifying vision for Europe, the euro is now viewed as a millstone around the neck of a continent crippled by vast debts, sluggish economies, and growing populist dissent. In Europe’s Orphan, leading economic commentator Martin Sandbu presents a compelling defense of the euro. He argues that rather than blaming the euro for the political and economic failures in Europe since the global financial crisis, the responsibility lies firmly on the authorities of the eurozone and its member countries. The eurozone's self-inflicted financial calamities and economic decline resulted from a toxic cocktail of unforced policy errors by bankers, politicians, and bureaucrats; the unhealthy coziness between finance and governments; and, above all, an extreme unwillingness to restructure debt. Sandbu traces the origins of monetary union back to the desire for greater European unity after the Second World War. But the euro’s creation coincided with a credit bubble that governments chose not to rein in. Once the crisis hit, a battle of both ideas and interests led to the failure to aggressively restructure sovereign and bank debt. Ideologically informed choices set in motion dynamics that encouraged more economic mistakes and heightened political tensions within the eurozone. Sandbu concludes that the prevailing view that monetary union can only work with fiscal and political union is wrong and dangerous—and risks sending the continent into further political paralysis and economic stagnation. Contending that the euro has been wrongfully scapegoated for the eurozone’s troubles, Europe’s Orphan charts what actually must be done for the continent to achieve an economic and political recovery.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 25. Feb 2021) 0aDebt reliefzEuropean Union countries. 0aEuro. 0aEurozone. 0aFinancial criseszEuropean Union countries. 0aMonetary policyzEuropean Union countries. 0aMoneyzEuropean Union countries. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Money & Monetary Policy.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015z978311044418640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978140087342540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400873425423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781400873425.jpg  a978-3-11-044418-6  PUP eBook-Package Pilot Project 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles